I made this as directed and have to say I did not enjoy it and will not make it again. Way too much acid for the amount of honey. I doubled the honey and the sauce was still to acidic and watery.

Rating: 4
I only had thighs (with skin & bone) on hand, so I amended the cooking time by keeping my fingers crossed and hoping for the best. The sauce really kicked up my potatoes, which I mashed with butter and a mexican cheese blend. This was super easy, and as someone who has been accused of "cooking like a scientist", it made my night and my guests very pleased. This will be added to my rotation.

Rating: 4
I loved this recipe; what you choose to serve it with along with the quality of Sherry- Vinegar and the correct reduction can put this over the top. I decided to use O Sherry-Vinegar from the O Olive Oil Company and I made sure to reduce it to 1/2 Cup. I served it with Basmati rice cooked in chicken broth and Sugar Snap Peas as my vegetable.

Rating: 4
We've made this twice now and think it's a fantastic dish made exactly as directed. The crisp skin is delicious - don't be shy with the salt and pepper at the prep stage. My only wish would be that the sauce be more creamy and less thin.

Rating: 4
Great chicken dish. I've made it a few times, and its an easy weeknight meal that is gourmet. This last time I ran out of sherry vinegar and subbed 1/2 white wine vinegar and 1/2 balsamic and it worked great. I also had to use skinless breasts and although it would have been better with the skin for the crispiness, it was still a great dish. The sauce goes well with mashed potatoes or couscous.

Rating: 3
Be sure to use Sherry Vinegar... don't substitute!

Rating: 3
I had some misgivings due to previous reviews, so I took the suggestion of adding two tablespoons of honey as opposed to two teaspoons. The result was just the right mix of tart and sweet. I'm not an accomplished cook so I was surprised by how much the sauce smoked. My dog kept barking at the smoke detector and I panicked a little. The smell also permeated the house in a not good way. Crack the windows while you're cooking and keep the vent fan on. I served with mashed potatoes to soak up the extra sauce, and threw the chicken under the broiler for a few minutes to crisp the skin up even more. Yum.

